solution.p:
(b) The function x^5-x+k has a root at x=x_0 if and only if x^5-x=-k at x=x_0. So the number of distinct real roots of x^5-x+k is the number of times the curve y=x^5-x crosses the horizontal line y=-k. The local maximum of x^5-x (when x=-\dfrac{1}{\root{4}\of{5}}) is \dfrac{4}{5\root{4}\of{5}}, and the local minimum of x^5-x (when x=\dfrac{1}{\root{4}\of{5}}) is -\dfrac{4}{5\root{4}\of{5}}. So, looking at the graph of x^5-x above, we see that the number of distinct real roots of x^5-x+k is
1 when |k| \gt \dfrac{4}{5\root{4}\of{5}}
2 when |k|=\dfrac{4}{5\root{4}\of{5}}
3 when |k| \lt \dfrac{4}{5\root{4}\of{5}}

